data.name: label9.Text
data.value: Aunt Node - This node is an "aunt" to the previous parent's children, and a "sibling" to the previous parent. The current submenu will be closed and this node will be the new parent. All subsequent nodes will be Child Nodes unless otherwise specified.

data.name: label11.Text
data.value: Grand Node - This node is a "grandparent" to the previous parent's children, and a "parent" to the previous parent (unless at root). For each '<' symbol, one submenu will be closed and this node will be up that many layers from the previous. All subsequent nodes will be Child Nodes unless otherwise specified.

data.name: label14.Text
data.value:
To start using, you'll first need to create a command. Click the '+' button at the top right of the Edit window. Name this command under "Display Text", and paste the actual command in the "Command Text" box. Click "Save" to store this command in the list, and click "Run" to test the command. Avoid using the '~' character at all. Avoid using the '>' and '<' characters unnecessarily.
The contents of the Command Text box are executed within a script, so multiple commands can be added. The list of Commands is presented as a tree, so you can organize your commands into "tiers" or "folders".
See the "Nodes" and "Keywords" sections to learn more.

data.name: label13.Text
data.value:
Dev Commander is a System Tray tool that allows you to call batch scripts you've defined. You can customize a list of pre-programmed CMD commands, executable with a click.
For ease of use, it's recommended you pin the icon to your system tray and add a shortcut to your startup folder: (AppData\Roaming\Microsoft\Windows\Start Menu\Programs\Startup) to keep the tool running at all times, ready for whenever you need it.
